description.text:
A slight modification from the Secret Heart Box adding a shelf along the inside of the cleave line on the top layer. This avoids the problem of filaments pulling the edge out of shape if the first fill is anything other than in the X direction.

My worst problem for the original Secret Heart box was in the bridging for the top piece. It appears that many are printing with PLA and with aggressive cooling that seems to work really well. I wanted to get ABS to work, and the one remaining problem was the ABS strand along the cleave line for both the upper sections and lower sections would get stretched by the first layer fill. One solution is obviously to use a slicer that does the top fill along the Y and X axis (as emmett's shows). However, the slicer I've been using insists on doing a 45 degree top fill and that would drag the filament along the cleave line out of sorts.

Having to pick and choose slicers just rankles with so many builds, so instead I added a small shelf along the inside top cleave line that allows the top layer to fill in any direction as it's hardened enough by the time the fill layer is required. That worked great! No supports required.

It's the first time I'd seen or used SCAD and I was blown away by emmett's ingenuity and clear spatial reasoning.

description.text:
First of all, props to JediTrooper for doing a fantastic job modeling Rey's Staff.

In JediTrooper's photos of the ends of the staff, I could really notice the edges of the conical part, listed as Part_2-6-22. I don't know if that was a deliberate design choice, but I prefer a smoother cone. So I redesigned it!

The original part's cone has 24 vertices all around. The one I built in Autodesk 123D Design has 128. I tried my best to keep the dimensions the same as the original STL file, though there are likely to be small differences.

If wondering at what scale to print this piece at (for different sized staffs), know that my file has an inner diameter of 18 mm, similar to that of the original STL file.

I have included two versions of the piece, depending on how your slicer and printer work:

  • Part2Smoothed_WithoutWall is my original creation where the cone thickness approaches 0 mm toward the top.
  • Part2Smoothed_WithWall adds an interior wall 0.4 mm thick so slicers don't chop the top off. The inner diameter is still 18 mm, but the entire piece is slightly bigger to compensate.

I've included an example of the difference in slicing using Cura 15.04.6 with a screenshot. Notice how the part without the wall (right side) has its top clipped off compared to the one with the wall (left side).

The raw file is also there in case someone wants to make their own changes.

Enjoy!

I saw various styles of guitar string winders out there, but I felt that most appeared to have little structural integrity because most were 100% 3d printed parts, and/or the action seemed as though it wouldnt be very smooth. I saw some that used a screw like I did, but the screws stuck out, which would scratch the tuners. I made this to fit a 40mm M3 screw perfectly, so that the socket cap is recessed, and the m3 nyloc nut is recessed as well.

Hardware:
-M3*40mm Socket Cap Screw
-624Z Bearing
-M3 Washers (one at the socket cap, and one between the bearing and handle)
-M3 Nyloc Nut

There is built in support (a .25 mm layer) for the nut trap and bearing trap overhangs. Simply use a hobby knife to cut out the hole. The bearing is meant to fit tight. Also note that if you print a fatter first layer, you might have to trim that layer a little in the nut trap and bearing trap.

I made this custom for my acoustic so it might not fit other guitars. I recommend printing the body first to see if it fits on your guitar's tuner. Feel free to request remixes/tweaks to fit your guitar.

title: Improved Ball and Socket Joint for PCB Workstation

description.text:
This is an improved ball and socket joint for giufini's excellent PCB Workstation with Articulated Arms.

The author used HIPS for his ball and socket joints but I only print with PLA and PETG. With both materials, I ran into a number of problems getting the articulated arms to work well. Here's a summary of the problems I had:

  1. The socket ball wears quickly and the articulated arm becomes very loose
  2. The ball easily pops out of the socket when the travel limit of the arm is reached
  3. The arms don't bend with a very tight radius so moving the arm around frequently causes the balls to pop out

I tried both versions of the alternative ball and socket design with heat shrink tubing but the heat shrink quickly breaks down and gums up the socket. Plus, the bend radius is also reduced with the heat shrink.

So I took a stab at designing an improved ball and socket joint. The biggest requirement is that the ball remain the same size so it fits all of the accessories in the original project. Here's the mods I made to the design.

  1. Raised the ball away from the socket by about 2 millimeters - this improves the arm bend radius significantly and also makes it much harder for the ball to pop out of the socket when the travel limit of the arm is reached.
  2. Made the socket wrap around the ball about 1 millimeter farther down - this makes the ball stay in the socket better and also improves the stiffness of the arm with the greater surface area in contact.
  3. Made the inside diameter of the socket slightly smaller to stiffen the joint and keep it from loosening as much

I'm quite happy with the final result. All of the probe holders and accessories I printed still attach fine but I no longer have the problems with loose arms and balls popping out.

Enjoy!

description.text:
My wife is dutch. My kids are half-dutch. The Decemberists are from Portland. Whatever. I wanted to try my hand at something different so I turned the Crane Wife album art into an SVG file and tried to think of what kind of cool art I could 3D print from it.

This is an adapter for installing Carbon Rods with Magnetic Bearings onto the Geeetech Delta G2S printer. These were designed for use with my Universal Effector System and 3-Bearing Carriages, but should fit the original versions as well. Rod length is 215mm, weight (including adapters) is about 2/3 of what the original metal rods weighed.

You will need a full set of 12 adapters to complete installation of the 6 rods. M3x16mm screws are used to afix the adapters into the stock 6mm rod mounting holes. I suggest using locking style M3 nuts to keep everything tight.

license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This modified blower will be handy for those who have added an inductive sensor to their BQ Prusa i3.

I found another one that did not allow the lower nut to be inserted, I've corrected the problem by making the place where the sensor goes a little bit narrower.

I'd recommend to print this part in ABS as it lies very near the hotend, nevertheless I've used PLA and everything is OK.

I bought my sensor from Amazon : 3 wire Noncontact Inductive Proximity LJ12A3-4-Z

Connection:

You should disconnect the Z Endstop and instead plug your sensor the following way:

  • Brown: VCC (12V)
  • Blue: GND
  • Black: (Signal) With a diode like a 1N4148/1N4140, plug the cathode of the diode to the black wire and the anode to the processor input.

If you plug it this way you won't need a voltage divider and regulator some people suggest, it's easier and it works great.

As for the firmware, you should uncomment ENABLE_AUTO_BED_LEVELING on Configuration.h and change the settings to match your setup.

I hope you enjoy it!

EDIT :

Check out my new design which enables you to have LED lights on top of the inductive sensor! https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2348123

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

title: Large Bed Mendel Max Printer Variant

description.text:
This is a larger-format printer in the style of the Mendel Max, but with completely new/custom parts designed to give a 12" x 12" x 12" build volume. This was undertaken as a group project by the Port City Makerspace in Portsmouth, NH to provide us with a new piece of equipment - but from the start of the project, the intent was always to document the build and make it available to anyone. The complete build documentation - instructions, pics & videos, notes, and comprehensive BOM are not yet available. For now, you can try to scrape together some useful information from the project wiki here: https://sites.google.com/site/pcmakerspacewiki/home/project However, there is a lot of information that has not been moved up to the wiki yet. As such, please consider this printer an advanced build, that should only be attempted by an individual or group with previous reprap-style experience. That said, In essence, it builds just like a Mendel Max. Notes:
On our printer (named "Gipsy Danger" because it's a big-ass 'bot), all printed parts are printed in PLA at 70% infill and .3mm layer height. This is just for reference, do whatever floats your boat.
All linear motion in the axes are accomplished with 10mm smooth rods and linear bearings (LM10UU or equivalent). In the pics of our build, we use a monster (~1") smooth rod with bearing blocks for one slide of the Y axis, but that's just beacause someone gave that to us for free. If nobody gave you a monster smooth rod & blocks identical to ours, then you should print the corner pieces that have the 10mm rod holders on both sides, and use three or four bearing "outriggers" to support the sliding bed.
Use whatever electronics you'd like - RAMPs, a Printrboard, or build yourself a reprap Generation 7 Electronics board like we did.
Our machine uses a custom X-carriage and a direct-drive extruder mechanism designed by one of our members. It should be printed in ABS to resist heat, or you should install a wooden block as an insulator if you want to use PLA. We did a custom extruder setup to allow room for dual extruders; if you don't want that, you can probably adapt the existing x-carriage for a singe Wade's-style extruder. Maybe we'll have time to set up a generic platform at some point.
We'll add more notes as we can. Good luck!
  • Group build team at PCMS
    (portcitymakerspace.com)

Build steps: Here's what you'll need -
1 set of aluminum extrusion parts:
Qty 2 top supports
Qty 4 diagonal supports
Qty 4 base uprights
Qty 8 base horizontal segments
A complete set of printed parts:
2 each of the left and right corner supports - they are symmetrical front-to-rear so two of each will give you the 4 you need
2 Z motor mounts
2 Z-axis rod top supports
1 Y motor mount
1 set of Y-belt idler parts
1 pair of X axis ends - one end has the motor mount and the other end has the idler
1 X-carriage
1 or 2 extruder assemblies
2 z-motor couplers
Qty 6 10mm smooth rods, about 14" in length
Qty 12 LM10UU linear bearings
Qty 2 Acme lead screws & matching flange nuts
Qty 2 drive belts & matching pulleys
5 standard NEMA 17 stepper motors (6 for dual extrusion). This bot is big - go high-torque with heat sinks if you can.
Electronics
Power supply - 12V 30A ebay special is what we used.
Endstop switches
Heated bed (optional). We used Qty 6"x6" tiles wired with switches so we only have to heat the front left bed for small prints. You can limit your print area to that tile by temporarily setting your slicer to 150mm x 150mm print area. If you go this route, you'll need to use a separate 12v rail rated high enough to drive 4 tiles, and trigger it with a solid-state relay connected to the heater output of the electronics board. Works for us, anyway. :)

title: naze32 vibration damping mount (inexpensive earplug edition)

description.text:
As always, the most recent OpenSCAD code is here, on github: https://github.com/beckdac/naze32_vibro_mount

This thing is a mount for the common f450 clone and family for a naze32 rev6 (might work with other revs) with 3M (and other) earplug as vibration dampeners. Simply pull them through the 5mm holes and wait a few minutes while the memory phone expands. It helps to use mm ruler or digital caliper to verify the offsets are equal and then do a calibrate accel in cleanflight config, which is where this has been tested. And now more recently with iNav.

Printer:

MakerFarm i3v 10

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

No

Resolution:

.2

Infill:

20%

Notes:

Go for it!

Roll up the earplugs in your fingies until they fit in the 5mm holes. Patience, a small amount helps. Then push it through. The 3M brand is resilient and cheaply available and will tolerate being pulled through with tweezers. Make sure the naze32 is level on the plugs and ensure enough of the plugs protrudes from either side so it won't pop off on a hard landing. Which you will have until your G-tune your cleanflight.
OpenSCAD ftw! It'd be awesome if OpenSCAD wasn't a rendering dog, but hey, we love it anyway.

Also see AS220s:
http://www.as220.org/labs/drawbot/ I liked the polargraph rotating axial mount, but since I do not have the suitable bearings, I printed sliding rings from pla. The fit is quite close, and with some Teflon spray they appear to work great!
This has still to be mounted and tested. Notice the tidy desk ;-) Other available sources are Makerblock's build http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:16384 JohnA's gondola:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:12557

The machine was commissioned early february, the mechanics work as expected. The firmware (see below) is now working perfectly with the controller. If you download the current files, double-check in particular the distance between the servo mounts on the hub, they lack maybe 1mm. An improved model is in the works. You will need to print: 2 x stepperbase
2 x plate1
1 x hub
2 x hubspacer
2 x hubring
1 x hubcap You will need some form of T5 pulley, either printed or metallic (I went with metallic ones) and as in kritzlerbot, 6m of T5 belt. Alternatively, you substitute that with a small spool and nylon monofilament, for a much more affordable solution. You can also use ball chain instead. See http://www.thingiverse.com/tag:ball_chain The 2xNEMA17 motors are totally overkill but I had them around. Each one is fastened with 3 m3x35 bolts. I added a m4 washer between pieces to gain in height, this will be added to next version. The stepperbases and plates are symmetrical to simplify part multiplication and printing. You can optionally fit 3 small 624ZZ bearings on an m4 bolt to provide more contact between the belt and the pulley. A thin m4 washer between the plastic and the bearing may be of some use. The hub or gondola's axis hosts: one spacer, two rings, one spacer, one cap fastened with one or two m4 bolts. Near the tip of the pen set three m4 nuts and bolts to fasten the pen. I killed a boarduino by plugging simultenously two 5v power sources, so I settled for an on-the-test-board ATMega328 and two stepsticks. This is Nukpana, fetchling sorceress. Fetchlings are descendants of humans how once migrated to the Plane of Shadows. The have mysterious powers and skin colours in all variants of grey, though neither of those things show up on flatminis. Nukpana wants to be a manipulator of shadows, but so far in our campaign her more effective spells have been those putting people to sleep and those making surfaces slippery. She follows Sigismund mostly out of a desire to adventure and make friends.

Based on grumpyrobot's female blank and made with Tinkercad. The hair came from a clipart by GDJ which I modified in Inkscape. Edit it here

Sometimes the spikes on Flatminis equipment print badly for me, I've found that it helps to print them separately. My model is standing on my oblong base, but the main STL includes the standard 25mm Flatminis base. Both are included as separate STLs.

While he might look as a Norman knight on foot, this is actually Sigismund, fetchling paladin of Erelm Brimirsdräpe and acting ambassador of the fetchling-realm of Talheim. He's a bit poor right now, so he has settled for mail armour until proper plate can be acquired. Until then, he wields a more defensive sword-and-shield combo instead of a great weapon. Why he chooses to go without a helm is, however, beyond me. Sigismunds entourage consists of Vaughan, Nukpana and Sir Woo-Jung Mi-Rhun.

The mail didn't come out all that great (though it would probably be improved with some cleaning with a sharp knife) but I think it gets the job down. My printer has trouble printing without rafts, without one the shield would probably have been smoother.

I made it with Tinkercad, starting with grumpyrobot's male blank. Customize it here.

title: Prusa i3 Y axis belt holder

description.text:
This Y axis belt holder is for a specific Prusa i3 variant - ANet A8.

The original Y belt holder was laser-cut acrylic, which presented 2 problems:

  1. It held the Y belt at a level higher than pulleys at both ends, which resulted in excessive vibration when the plates is near the minimum of maximum of Y axis.

  2. It felt pretty brittle. I wasn't too sure how much I could tighten it. As the result, I was unable to tighten the Y belt tensioner sufficiently.

This design solves both problems.

You need to duplicate it in your slicer as you will need 2 sets.

It's designed to print without support. Please make sure you break it into individual parts, and rotate the parts appropriately.

The design is available at OnShape here so that anyone can customize it to their own size/need.

title: Cargo Area Anchor Point / Bungee Tie Down
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
This is an anchor point intended for use in automotive cargo area applications. The tie downs are designed to be installed on an interior panel of a car in the cargo area and only require that two 3mm holes be drilled to install it. The two part design functions as a clamp that sandwiches both sides of an interior panel to evenly distribute the load. This design is for both durability and holding power without deforming or warping the interior panel. In addition to the printed part you will need 2 M3 lock nuts and 2 M3 screws (the length of the screw will vary depending on the thickness of the panel that you want to install it on.)

I designed these for the parcel shelf in the rear of my Mustang to be able to bungee tie down packages, bags, or the occasional pizza. Loads shifting in a car can be very dangerous and if you're like me and enjoy driving spiritedly these will help keep everything in place! These would also be suitable for use in a trunk, the rear of an SUV, or even the cabin.

EDIT: At the suggestion of Reddit User "exdot" I've included a high load variant with a larger edge to edge loop for easier printing and additional durability. Also, I've gotten some feedback that not everyone has a small enough hex socket to fit in the back plate so I've went ahead and made an alternative back plate design as well.

title: Nissan Versa glove compartment latch mechanism
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
I own a 2011 Nissan Versa SL. I noticed one day that I was unable to open the glove compartment. The handle was broken. After a google search and a few telephone calls later, it seemed that the 50 cent part would cost over $100 and require replacing the entire glove compartment door. I found instructions on how to open the door.

A. With a flathead screw driver, carefully pry off the handle (from the side)
B. Push down into the notch, the retention mechanism to open the glove compartment
C. There are 2 philips head screws holding the mechanism in place.
D. The "nub" on the spring mechanisms is fragile and breaks over time.

See here (not my youtube video) : https://youtu.be/YQoSXJdJF3g
A tuber posted a video on how to open the glove: https://youtu.be/mhRDDm4y7fU

description.text:
This a remix of the popular Micro 105 FPV quad. The intent of this remix is to make the arms wide enough (3mm minimum) to put continuous strands of carbon fiber in as I am printing quads on a Markforged Mark Two. I also feel like it looks a bit less toyish than the standard frame with the single arms, but that's just personal opinion.

Want one printed but don't have access to a Markforged machine? Check out our page on 3Dhubs and have us make one for you!

https://www.3dhubs.com/buffalo/hubs/miller-3d

I was breaking a lot of ABS frames (just learning to fly, not very good yet) so I switched to nylon. While fantastically crashproof, the nylon v3 frames were very floppy which wasn't great. My work got a Mark Two recently so I figured this would be a good chance to take advantage of the shorter CFF length it can do vs. the Mark One.

V1 frame weighed in at 7.75g for top and bottom, is stiff enough (for me) and is entirely crashproof, I challenge anyone to break one of these frames. V1 base only has fiber in the arms, it did not path to the center of the frame. It is pretty flexible but once assembled with the carbon reinforced upper deck it gains a lot of strength.

I have yet to print V2/3 but it has been revised to use less nylon on the motor mounts (but requires a tiny bit of thin tape to hold them, I plan on using Kapton) and has carbon fiber pathed through the center of the bottom frame, so it should be a good bit stiffer than V1. Based on the material volumes the slicer tells me, it should weigh about 5.76g for the bottom only. I can probably cut some more weight by reducing the wall thicknesses in the middle, I had to extend them outwards to get carbon around the holes and I was too lazy to thin the inside out at the moment.

I just revised it again to cut some weight out of the center of the frame, v3 should now come in at about 5.1g.

The top has also been modified to path fiber. V1 only puts it around the perimeter which is good enough, really. It's the 13 degree top for fast forward flight, haven't made any of the other angles.

Once we get Onyx (new Markforged material, nylon with chopped fiber) I will try a print in that with continuous carbon as well, that should be plenty strong and stiff for any application.

If anyone wants one of these printed and doesn't have access to a Mark Two, I can probably print some. It might be a bit more expensive than if it were my personal printer, but I'm sure I can help some people out if needed. You could probably get away with just using my lower frame with a standard ABS upper, that part doesn't really break much in the first place.

I plan on printing v3 frame in the next couple days. I've extensively crashed v1 over the past few days and it's tough as nails.

Update: I've printed the v3 frame with Onyx (chopped carbon in nylon) and also have CFF strands of carbon fiber in the part. It's super strong and still crashproof! Check out the photo of the bottom frame with a 8lb granite block on it, there's barely any deflection. Very impressive strength from a five gram part. The combined frame weighs 7.5g and my quad weighs 38.5g without a battery.

description.text:
This is a scale model (1/32 - Gauge 1) of a small boxcar used in the late 1890s.
It uses the same frame as my Bobber Caboose (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1363887) but almost everything had to be reworked.

Printer:

Vertex K8400

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.1 and 0.2 mm

Infill:

30-40%

Notes:

Everything is printed in ABS on a heated bed (100°) coated with a 3D adhesive spray.
The sliding doors and their mechanism are to scale hence very small and thin. The doors are printed vertically at low speed. The brackets and rails at 0.1 mm layer height. Rods shafts and other small parts are also printed at 0.1 mm.

The roof is best printed vertically (file with brim). There's a file without brim for those who can't.

Parts 24 to 27a are not on the exploded view.

Assembly instructions

To avoid having screws on the rooftop the roof is bolted to the roof truss from under. To put the roof in place you'll have to insert the ends of the truss in the notches inside the cabin. So you'd better check if they fit easily before trying to do it. Some filing/sanding may be needed.

The wall raisers, rails and door brackets are glued to the cabin and the door (PVC glue for ABS, super glue for PLA). Some filing may be needed for the upper brackets to have them sliding easily on the rail.
The rungs, brake platform, rods etc are glued to the cabin. The 2 lower rungs must be slightly bended downwards.
The axle bearings can be screwed from inside the cabin with 2x8 mm screws. The front and rear boxes for the uncoupling mechanism too.
I'm using 3mm steel axles about 67 mm long. If needed, drill the holes in the axles bearings to 3.2 mm.

New 2016-11-22 : I've designed a knuckle coupler fitting the boxcar (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1908821). If you already printed it you'll have to drill a 2 mm hole in the cabin floor for the screw holding the gearbox cover. Otherwise there's a new version of the cabin with the holes.

title: Groove Effector for Delta Printers
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
I had the idea of designing this effector after seeing one published by Boofly at this link: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:520580.
In my version you can disassemble the extruder without having to break up the printer as happened to me with the effector that came to my printer.
The only thing to take into account and the triggering of the order Zmin limit switch for the leveling of the floor that must be soldered on pin NO because in this version of trigger is reversed, ie at the moment that the extruder touches the plan opens the switch snapping it.
I added the side cover and support for the leds
Please send me all your comment.
Good 3d printing at all

As you can see from the photos I used some pretty long screws because the springs that I have found on the market have a high resistance compared to their size, but with them I was able to adjust the extruder with a margin of 0.02mm. I preferred to use also the self-locking nuts because the normal ones unscrew because of printing vibrations, while as you can see from looking at a photograph of the nuts that hold the two halves of the collar on the moving plate effector are normal because these last I must be nuts fully tightened.

In what sense is difficult auto leveling the print head?
My firmware is to use the self-leveling function, although I personally made changes, with regard to the calibration of the plan I have adjusted the screw under the switch as long as I not hear the click at that point I unscrewed it until is not taken again, I have done adjustments raising and lowering the print head and got a gap of 0.2 / 0.1 mm in the 25 reading points.

comments.text: I was just thinking about the force in which the head is driven into the bed to get the switch to trigger and the stresses it places on the head and hardware itself. But I'm sure its fine since the heads are usually all metal, I was just thinking that if the plastic parts didn't slide smoothly enough or whatever... I actually don't use auto level, it doesn't feel precise enough, I find it easier to adjust manually via firmware and the kossel bed levelers that I designed. http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2092046

comments.text:
I think That the convenience of this 3D printer is precisely linked to the fact that it is not necessary calibrate to manually nothing, because before each printing the machine is calibrated every time alone, and as I told you I have changed the firmware so that it can take 25 references on my printing table which is made of glass.
As for the strength exercising the springs i've been able find the springs with a slight force, and in addition I have made their adjustments in settings of the slicing software.
Also I do not think that we need so much cool, you keep in mind that to speed up the process of heating and press i have also changed the print code to send the fan to 50% up to the printer almost ready and after the speed ports to 100%, in this way the head temperature drops back to 5/6 degrees and if I put the side cover that directs jet in the head the temperature drops even more.
